<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEW MELONES DAM BENEFITS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Maybe the expression "out of sight, out of mind" could be used to explain the 
miscalculations and inaccuracies presented in The Times' editorial ("Savoring a 
Dam Decision," Sept. 3) denouncing the value of the New Melones dam. But in all 
fairness to your readers and the numerous beneficiaries of this project, I feel 
those benefits bear repeating. 
</P>
<P>
In your editorial you say that the New Melones dam, located on the Stanislaus 
River, "provides very cheap power for a small number of Californians." 
</P>
<P>
The fact is power generated by the dam goes into the Central Valley Project 
power pool and is then sold to provide power for millions of Californians. New 
Melones generates enough electrical power to meet the annual electrical needs 
of approximately 72,000 households. 
</P>
<P>
The New Melones dam also provides significant water releases to improve water 
quality in the south delta; has saved millions of dollars in avoided flood 
damage costs; offers numerous recreational and fishery opportunities, and 
supplies necessary interim flows in the Stanislaus River for fish and wildlife. 
</P>
<P>
All of these benefits, of course, are in addition to 180,000 acre-feet of water 
supply available for municipal and agricultural uses. 
</P>
<P>
It should also be noted that the New Melones project provided significant 
assistance during the last three dry years, and is now being used as a water 
source to replace declining ground water tables in surrounding counties, and in 
some areas to fight sea water intrusion. 
</P>
<P>
Let me remind the editor that in 1974 the voters of California had the 
opportunity to pass an initiative thereby designating a stretch of the river 
where the New Melones dam is located as wild and scenic. That initiative was 
defeated. 
</P>
<P>
Finally, your readers may be interested to know that New Melones dam merely 
replaced a dam originally built in 1926 by two area irrigation districts. 
</P>
<P>
As you can see, the existence of the New Melones dam, as well as many other dam 
projects throughout the state can be easily justified. 
</P>
<P>
JOHN P. FRASER 
</P>
<P>
Executive Director 
</P>
<P>
General Counsel 
</P>
<P>
Association of California 
</P>
<P>
Water Agencies 
</P>
<P>
Sacramento 
</P>
</TEXT>
