<P>
A former nursing home aide was found guilty on charges that she smothered five 
incapacitated patients in a pact with her lesbian lover. A jury in Grand 
Rapids, Mich., deliberated five hours before finding Gwendolyn Graham guilty on 
five counts of first-degree murder and one count of conspiracy to commit murder 
in the 1987 deaths of patients at Alpine Manor Nursing Home. Graham, 26, faces 
mandatory life imprisonment without parole. The case rested largely on 
testimony by Catherine Wood, who said the two had formed a pact to suffocate 
patients so they would be bound to each other. Wood, who pleaded guilty to 
second-degree murder, faces up to life in prison when she is sentenced. 
