THE STATE; 
</P>
<P>
TOXINS FORCE SHELLFISH BAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The worst toxic contamination since 1980 has forced a quarantine of 
non-commercial harvesting of shellfish on the coastline of Del Norte, Humboldt 
and Mendocino counties. State Health Director Kenneth Kizer said mussel samples 
from the area had potentially life-threatening levels of the toxin that causes 
paralytic shellfish poisoning. He said toxin levels were the highest since 
paralytic shellfish poisoning was blamed for two deaths in 1980. The quarantine 
applies to clams, razor clams, cockles, scallops and other bivalve mollusks. 
Paralytic shellfish poisoning affects the nervous system after consumption of 
mussels and other shellfish that have fed on certain highly toxic marine 
organisms. Commercial harvesting is unaffected by the quarantine since there is 
a regulatory program to prevent shellfish with high levels of PSP toxin from 
reaching the market, Kizer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
