<P>
</P>
<P>
The Beverly Hills district has 4,700 students. The contract covers about 300 
employees -- teachers, counselors, librarians, nurses and others. 
</P>
<P>
The Santa Monica-Malibu district has 9,300 students. The contract covers about 
500 employees. 
</P>
<P>
The Los Angeles district has 600,000 students. The contract covers 32,000 
employees. 
</P>
<P>
*The Los Angeles teachers union disputes this figure, contending it includes 
benefits; without the benefits, the union says, the figure is about $38,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Table, SALARY COMPARISONS 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA092189-0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 110542 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
September 21, 1989, Thursday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Orange County Life; Part 9; Page 2; Column 4 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
356 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
MULTIFAMILY HOUSING PERMITS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Clipboard researched by Susan Davis Greene / Los Angeles Times. Graphics by 
Doris Shields / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Permits for multifamily housing units have been issued at a more subdued pace 
this year, contrasted with 1988. After six months, permits for 4,742 such units 
had been granted, 31% below the number for the comparable period last year (48% 
less than 1987 and 45% behind 1986). 
</P>
<P>
Although June's 1,185 was the highest monthly total since last September, it is 
the lowest June figure for any of the last four years. The decrease has been 
caused most notably by the comparative lack of activity in the unincorporated 
areas of the county, although several cities have also seen their numbers drop 
dramatically. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
