<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Arts Funding Debate 
</P>
<P>
By a vote of 264 to 153, the House took a procedural step against lawmakers 
wanting a sweeping reduction in federal support of art they deem offensive. 
This occurred as the House debated positions it should take in a House-Senate 
conference on an appropriations bill (HR 2788) covering the National Endowment 
for the Arts and other agencies. 
</P>
<P>
The vote prevented a direct House vote on whether to go along with tough Senate 
language on federal funding of art that some see as morally offensive. Jesse 
Helms (R-N.C.) wrote the Senate measure in response to the endowment's funding 
of projects that yielded photography of homosexual acts, naked children and a 
crucifix immersed in urine. The Helms amendment sought to ban federal funding 
to promote or produce art judged to be obscene, indecent or blasphemous. 
</P>
<P>
Members voting yes wanted to block a direct vote on the merits of the 
Senate-passed Helms amendment. 
</P>
