<P>
TEXAS AIR MAY SELL RESERVATION UNIT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Frank Lorenzo's troubled Texas Air Corp. is discussing the sale of its computer 
reservation system to a General Motors Corp. unit in a deal that could bring 
the airline concern as much as $400 million, according to a report published 
today. 
</P>
<P>
Unidentified sources cited in the Wall Street Journal confirmed that 
negotiations with Electronic Data Systems Corp. were advanced and that barring 
a snag, an agreement could be forged within several weeks. 
</P>
<P>
Analysts estimated that Texas Air's System One, the third-ranked computer 
reservation system in the airline industry, could fetch between $300 million 
and $400 million. 
</P>
<P>
Texas Air has given no indication of what it might do with the proceeds from 
any sale. 
</P>
